    - Lathander old
        
        Lathander found hope in Devon. He believed that as long as people like Devon existed, mortals still deserved their second chance. They were not beyond redemption, they could be guided and saved. 
        
        Unfortunately Devon was one day also affected by the plague. The disease spread through his body, leaving streaks of white patches on his skin, darkening his eyes. Soon he could no longer walk, talk and smile. He was dying. 
        
        In desperation to save only friend Lathander revealed himself to the mortalkind. He cured Devon of the dark curse and brought back his laughter. Some say Lathander gave a piece of his own divinity to the young prince, for since that day the boy’s eyes glowed radiant yellow. 
        
        After this, word soread across Aethermere, a god had returned. Lathander started helping mortals, he cleared the skies, so the sun can shine upon the lands a little more, he cured the lands, so people can finally grow crops,  he cleaned the waters to make them drinkable. 
        
        But even after these miracles people demanded more. People came to meet him, begged to help them. And Lathander complied, he couldn’t reject pleas of help. He helped the sick, took on their sorrows and pain.
        
        With each new wish fulfilled Lathander was growing weaker, his powers were vast but still finite. And even he couldn’t eradicate the plague. Seeing how helping people leaves a toll on the God, King Malvek decided that he had to separate Lathander from the people. Lathander was captured and imprisoned in his weakend state, so that only the King could have access to his powers.
        
        Malvek found a way to siphon Lathander’s powers and use them himself, he believed himself more capable with such powers to help people and destroy the Scourge curse.
        
         However, the king was inexperienced, lacked understanding and even with borrowed divine powers unable to fight the plague. Things only got worse, somehow the plague started spreading faster and the rising undead growing in numbers. The Kingdom of Argon was being destroyed, undead armies and plague spreading ever faster.
        
        Seeing the injustice to his friend, One day Devon snuck into his father’s dungeon and freed Lathander. Devon didn’t expect Lathander to help them, but to leave and to his own people, maybe they were right. But even then the God of Hope refused to give up on the mortals. 
        
        He didn’t have any strength or power within him left to fight plague and its corruption, but he had another plan. Void of most of his powers he was like an empty vessel, isntead of fighting the Scourge he decided to absorb it, take all of it into himself.
        
        That worked Lathander ended up saving Aethermoor like he wanted to. However, it came at the cost, the Scourge wasn’t destroyed it was just inside him. It hurt him, corrupted him from the inside, his very essence changed, no longer the kind and compassionate. Now hateful and punishing the God turned his attention to the mortals. 
        
        “Their struggles and mistakes are the crucible from which they must learn and grow”, his father said. He was wrong. Their struggles and mistakes were the crucibles by which they would be judged and punished.
        
        He killed Malvek, and everyone who wronged him. He established a new form government, where he is the leader to be praised and worshipped. He limited magic only to those who deserve and created a cast system. He went after those who opposed him and made a cruel example out of them. He brought back the ashen clouds to block the Sun, to stay away from his father’s sight and influence. 
        
        And thus the Sunless King was born. 
        
    - Lathander new
        
        Lathander, the God of Hope and son of the Sun God Pelon, was the youngest of the divine. Where the others were distant and resolute, he was always kind, compassionate and held a special tenderness for mortals. He could not bear to watch their pain and suffering.
        
        During the War of the Five Kings, he begged his father to intervene, to guide mortals away from further bloodshed. But Pelon refused.
        
        “Mortals, be they elves, dwarves, or humans - are not meant to rely on us to fix their troubles. Their struggles and mistakes are the crucible from which they must learn and grow,” his father said.
        
        Lathander could not accept that. To him, mortals were not beyond saving, they were lost. Abandoned. Left to suffer for the failings of kings and rulers.
        
        For centuries, he watched Aethermere burn. He saw cities fall, lands rot, and people turn on one another. When the Scourge was unleashed, it did not end just end the war it nearly ended everything. Millions died to the plague. Countless more to hunger and disease.
        
        Lathander could no longer endure it. Defying his father, he descended into the mortal realm in secret. For the first time, he walked among the people, felt their hunger, their fear, their fleeting joys. And it was there he met Devon, heir to Argon.
        
        Devon was everything the world was not - kind, hopeful, untouched by the cruelty around him. He laughed easily, dreamed freely, and believed that things could be better.
        
        Lathander saw himself in the boy. They became inseparable. Sneaking beyond the castle walls, running through open fields, hiding from guards speaking of futures neither fully understood, but both desperately wanted.
        
        For the first time in centuries, Lathander felt hope. He believed that as long as people like Devon existed, mortals were still worth saving. 
        
        Then Devon fell to the Scourge. The sickness spread quickly leaving streaks of white patches on his skin and darkening his eyes. Soon, he could no longer walk, speak, smile. He was dying.
        
        Desperate, Lathander broke his final boundary. He revealed himself to mortal kind. He cured Devon of the dark curse and brought back his laughter. Some say Lathander even gave a piece of his own divinity to the young prince, for from that day forward, the boy's eyes glowed with a radiant yellow light.
        
        Word spread across Aethermere, a god had returned. And Lathander answered. He cleared the skies, allowing sunlight to touch the land once more. He restored the soil so crops could grow, cleansed the waters, and eased the suffering of the people.
        
        But it was never enough. They came in greater numbers. Begging. Pleading. Demanding. And Lathander could not refuse. He healed the sick, took on their pain, and gave of himself again and again until his strength began to fail. His power, though vast, was not endless. And even he could not fully stop the Scourge.
        
        Seeing how helping others drained the god, King Malvek decided that Lathander had to be separated from the people. In his weakened state, Lathander was captured and imprisoned, so that only the king could access his power.
        
