        Malvek found a way to siphon Lathander's power and use it for himself. He believed himself more capable of wielding such power to help the people and destroy the Scourge.
        
        But he was wrong. The power was not his to control. The Scourge worsened. It spread faster, the undead grew in number, and the kingdom, he fought so hard to build, began to crumble.
        
        Seeing the mistakes of his father and injustice done to his friend, Devon descended into the dungeons and freed Lathander. He did not ask for help, only that Lathander leave, return to the gods, and abandon a world that had taken so much from him.
        
        But even then, the God of Hope refused to give up on mortals. Broken, betrayed, weak he would do all he could to help. Though he had no strength left to fight the Scourge, he found another way. 
        
        If he could not destroy it - he would contain it. He became a vessel. Lathander drew the Scourge into himself, absorbing its corruption, its death, its endless hunger. And it worked. The plague vanished, undead armies fell still. He saved Aetheremere.
        
        However, the Scourge was not destroyed, it lived on within him, twisting his nature, corrupting his soul. The God of Hope was nore more. Where there had once been compassion, there was now judgment. Where there had once been mercy, there was now wrath.
        
        “Their struggles and mistakes are the crucible from which they must learn and grow”, his father said. He was wrong. Their struggles and mistakes were the crucibles by which they would be judged and punished.
        
        He summoned the ashen clouds back, swallowing the sun and sealing his father's gaze from the world below. And in the cold darkness that remained, Lathander began his cleansing.
        
        Malvek was the first to fall. Then came the lords, the betrayers, the liars, any who had led the world to ruin. 
        
        He did not grant them mercy. Mercy was for those who deserved a second chance. And he had learned, at last, that mortals did not deserve second chances. They deserved justice.
        
        From the ashes, Lathander reshaped Aethermere in his image. Magic was restricted, granted only to those deemed worthy. A rigid order was imposed. Those who opposed him were made examples of, swiftly and brutally.
        
        The people learned to kneel, to obey, to fear. And in time, they have forgotten his origin. They called him by a new name. One whispered with care, spoken with trembling lips and averted eyes.
        
        The Sunless King.
        
        He had saved Aethermere. He had ended the war. He had stopped the plague. And he would never let them destroy themselves again.
        
    - Malvek
        
        The Neverwinter Woods, father used to tell me of the days before the war when he would climb those tall majestic, towering trees. I hope to one day see this place restored, to see children running and climbing the trees again, not worrying about survival, hunger and death. 
        
        Our province is dying, people are starving, villages getting raided and rulers are only looking for a way to hold on to power. Something has to change, or Argon will fall. 
        
        Axelim and his followers are dead, for some reason people chose me to lead them. I don’t know if I can, but I’ll try my best. I’ll save Argon and all of Aethermere. 
        
        Our people scattered, weakened and divided. If this is to continue, all of life will be destroyed on the continent. I made a decision, we will leave our homeland and its walls to set out and seek allies and unite. 
        
        People are desperate and scared, they are afraid of change even when they have nothing to lose. Many refused, those who wanted alliance are not willing to support our cause and leave their lands too. I need to show them the way forward, I need to show them hope. 
        
        Elthont province was the first one to positively respond with our alliance offer. This was a pivoting point, it showed others that uniting and working together was possible. Together we made the largest and strongest alliance in Aetheremere.
        
        Other provinces have become more hostile to us. They whisper I am seeking to conquer them, to take their lands and become their tyrant. They are attacking our delivery caravans and stealing our resources. 
        
        The council was growing less patient with me, my goal and this alliance is falling apart. I thought that by getting more provinces to join, by working together we could achieve greater things, but we can’t even agree on anything now. Every meeting is just a petty squabble, everyone is concerned about themselves and their own. 
        
        I’ve made a mistake. To achieve my goal we don’t need council or allies. We need a strong leader, someone who can make the difficult choices and bear the responsibility. I will become that someone. 
        
        My plan worked, the council members were trapped and forced to sign the contract and choose me as their leader, until the whole continent is united. Those who rejected would have been hanged. None chose this option, it’s funny how quickly their convictions die when they have something on the line. 
        
        Things went easier as I had the largest army and people followed me. Many provinces willingly joined us, others were forced and some had to be made an example. I am not proud of what I did, but someone had to do it, for the future of our kids for the survival of all our kind. 
        
        It was finally done, all of Aethermere is united together. Nothing really feels different, people still rarely see the sun, many are starving and the Scourge still troubles everyone. We’ve managed to contain it better, as one kingdom we are more united, more organized, more capable to protect itself. Catte offered to the council that I stay the King, that these people need me. He’s right, there is still so much work to be done.
        
        I built walls, cities, united the continent, but its still not enough. I have to eradicate the Scourge, for Devon. He will grow in the land full of sun and greenery. I will make sure of it. 
        
        The Scourge got Devon. He is dying. I’ve tried every healer, every doctor and arcane practitioner, but to no avail. Then the gods heard my prayers and sent Hope. 
        
        Lathander was not what I expected. Such grand power, but he seems so naive and simpleminded. That boy doesn’t think long term, he isn’t willing to make difficult choices. After revealing himself I was forced to witness how weak he is growing from helping everyone. It pains me to do this, but he is not capable of saving us, he is not worthy of the power. 
        
        Devon has always been soft hearted. I expected him to didn’t like what I did to Lathander, he doesn’t need to understand me. He can hate me for all he wants, but I am doing the right thing. Only history will judge me.
        
        I was wrong. I thought i understood the divine powers, but they are not mine to wield. The power has the intent which must be abided to, if not the power rejects you it, it doesn’t listen, doesn’t do as you will it. It’s too late to turn back now, I’ll do with what I have. 
        
    - Malvek new
        
        Father used to tell me stories of the Neverwinter Woods, of towering trees that touched the sky, of children climbing their branches without fear.
        I have never seen them that way.
        One day, I will. One day, this land will heal. Children will laugh again - not starve.
        
        Argon is dying. Villages burn. People starve. Bandits roam freely while rulers cling to power like it still means something. If nothing changes, there will be nothing left to rule.
        
        Axelim is dead. His followers… what remains of them… have chosen me to lead. I don’t know why. I am no savior. But I will not refuse. If no one else will act, then I will.
        
        We cannot survive like this, scattered, divided, weak. I have made my decision. We leave Argon. We seek allies. We unite… or we die separately.
        
        They are afraid. Even now, with nothing left to lose, they fear change more than death. Some refuse outright. Others listen, but will not act. Hope alone is not enough. I must show them.
        
        Elthont has agreed to stand with us. The first. A small victory, but enough. Others are beginning to listen. For the first time, unity feels… possible.
        
        Whispers follow us now. They say I seek power. That I will conquer, not unite. Caravans are attacked. Supplies stolen. They fear me more than the world ending around them.
        
        The council grows less patient with me. My goal, this alliance, is falling apart. I thought that by bringing more provinces together, we could achieve greater things. But now we cannot even agree on anything. Every meeting is a petty squabble. Everyone is concerned only with themselves.
        
        I have made a mistake. To achieve my goal, we don't need a council. We don't need allies. We need a strong leader. Someone who can make the difficult choices and bear the responsibility. I will become that someone.
        
        It is done. They signed. Some willingly. Most did not. Those who refused… reconsidered when faced with the consequences. Strange, how quickly conviction fades when life is at stake.
        
        It is finally done. All of Aethermere is united. Nothing feels different. People still rarely see the sun. Many are still starving. The Scourge still troubles everyone. But we have contained it better. As one kingdom, we are more united, more organized, more capable of protecting ourselves.
        
        They want me to be their king. They say I am needed. They are right. This is not finished.
        
        I have built walls. Cities. Order. Still, it is not enough. The Scourge must end. For Devon. He will not grow up in this dying world. I will see to it.
        
        The Scourge has taken him. My son is dying. I have tried everything. Healers. Scholars. Magic. Nothing works. If the gods still listen, now would be the time to prove it.
        
        Then the gods heard my prayers. They sent Hope.
        
        He is… not what I expected. So much power, and yet so naive. He gives and gives, without thought of cost or consequence. He will burn himself out. He cannot save this world.
        
        Devon looks at me differently now. He does not understand what must be done. That is fine. He does not need to understand. History will.
        
        I have done what was necessary. Lathander is contained. His power is in better hands now. No more waste. No more weakness.
        
        I was wrong. This power… it resists me. It is not a tool. It does not obey. It has a will, an intent. And it rejects mine. But it is too late to turn back now. Not after everything. Not after all the blood it took to get here. 
        
