Here’s a series of historical-style entries you can use as records, rumors, or lore fragments about Gravehold and the Sunless King’s descent into tyranny:

⸻

Year 12 of the Sunless Reign — The Edict of Ash
Following his rise, the Sunless King declared that all arcane practice must be sanctioned by the Crown. Independent mages were branded as threats to order. Several were publicly executed in Gravehold’s central square—burned beneath blackened braziers as a warning. The people watched in silence. Hope had already begun to dim.

⸻

Year 18 — The First Purge of Bastards
Rumors spread of illegitimate children bearing magic. The King’s Inquisitors were dispatched. Entire districts were searched. Families hid their children—or turned them in. Many vanished. The official records call it “necessary cleansing.” The streets remember it as something else.

⸻

Year 25 — The Black Tithe
To sustain the kingdom’s failing lands, the Crown imposed a new tithe—not of coin, but of life. Each province was required to “offer” a number of citizens for labor, experimentation, or “arcane necessity.” Refusal meant collective punishment. Compliance became survival.

⸻

Year 31 — The Silence Decree
Speaking against the Crown became treason. Informants were rewarded. Neighbors turned on one another. Public executions increased. Bodies were left hanging for days as reminders. Gravehold grew quieter.

⸻

Year 37 — The Burning of Elthont
The province of Elthont, once the first to ally with Malvek, rebelled against the Crown. They demanded autonomy and an end to the tithes. The Sunless King responded personally. The rebellion was crushed within days. The capital city was set ablaze. Survivors were enslaved or executed. Elthont was erased from official maps.

⸻

Year 42 — The Veil of Ash
The skies above Gravehold darkened further. The Sunless King summoned a permanent shroud of ash to block out the sun entirely. Crops worsened, but the King claimed it was necessary—to shield the realm from “greater threats” and divine interference. The people began calling him the Sunless King openly.

⸻

Year 48 — The Second Inquisition Reform
The Inquisitors were granted expanded authority. No longer just hunters of rogue magic, they became judges and executioners. Trials were deemed unnecessary. Their word became law. Even nobles feared them.

⸻

Year 55 — The Broken Rebellion
A coalition of nobles and military leaders attempted a coordinated uprising within Gravehold itself. It failed before it began. The leaders were captured and publicly executed. Their families were stripped of status, their names erased. From this point on, no large-scale rebellion would rise again.

⸻

Year 63 — The Doctrine of Worth
The King formalized the caste system. Magic, food, and protection were distributed based on “worth”—a measure defined solely by loyalty and usefulness to the Crown. The lower classes were left to starve, while the elite clung to survival.

⸻

Year 70 — The Withering Years
Reports indicate worsening conditions across all provinces. The Scourge, though diminished, still lingers. Crops fail more frequently. The King’s responses grow harsher. Entire villages have been abandoned or “relocated.” No records exist of where.

⸻

Year 82 — The Hollow Court
The royal court of Gravehold is said to be empty of dissent. Advisors either agree—or disappear. The Sunless King rules without opposition. Some claim he rarely appears in public anymore. Others say when he does, his presence alone causes fear to take hold.

⸻

