Here’s a longer, more “official-history” version—spanning centuries—written in a tone that frames the Sunless King as a necessary, even benevolent ruler, while still leaving subtle cracks for players to notice:

⸻

Year 0 of the Sunless Era — The Ascension
In the aftermath of the Scourge’s devastation, Lathander, now the Sunless King, rose to rule Aethermere. Having taken the burden of the plague upon himself, he ushered in a new age—one not of fleeting hope, but of order, stability, and survival.

⸻

Year 47 — The Edict of Guidance
To prevent the misuse of arcane power that once nearly destroyed the world, the King established strict oversight of magic. Only those deemed worthy and disciplined were permitted to wield it. This ensured that magic would serve the people, not endanger them.

⸻

Year 112 — The Founding of Gravehold
Gravehold was established as the central seat of power—a fortress city designed to withstand both rebellion and the remnants of the Scourge. It became a symbol of unity, strength, and protection under the King’s rule.

⸻

Year 184 — The Inquisitorial Mandate
The Inquisitors were formally organized as the King’s direct agents. Their purpose: to root out dangerous magic, lingering Scourge corruption, and threats to stability. Their efficiency brought a new era of safety, especially in regions once plagued by chaos.

⸻

Year 263 — The First Purification Campaigns
Reports of unstable magic among unregistered individuals led to targeted interventions. Though difficult, these actions prevented the rise of uncontrolled spellcasters who could have brought ruin once again. The Crown reaffirmed its duty to protect the many over the few.

⸻

Year 341 — The Ashen Veil
To shield Aethermere from divine interference and lingering celestial instability, the King raised the Ashen Veil—a protective shroud across the skies. While it dimmed the sun, it stabilized the environment and safeguarded the realm from forces beyond mortal control.

⸻

Year 417 — The Doctrine of Worth
To ensure fair distribution of limited resources, the King introduced the Doctrine of Worth. Citizens were granted status and provisions based on contribution and loyalty, encouraging unity, purpose, and societal balance in a harsh world.

⸻

Year 506 — The Elthont Reformation
The province of Elthont resisted central authority, threatening the fragile unity of the realm. The King intervened decisively. Though the conflict was brief, its resolution preserved the greater peace and prevented a wider collapse.

⸻

Year 688 — The Consolidation of Provinces
Through diplomacy and, when necessary, force, remaining independent regions were brought under the Crown. This ensured consistent protection, resource management, and defense against the Scourge across all of Aethermere.

⸻

Year 821 — The Second Inquisitorial Expansion
As new threats emerged, the Inquisitors were granted broader authority to act swiftly without bureaucratic delay. Their presence became a reassurance—where they walked, corruption did not take root.

⸻

Year 1034 — The Era of Stability
For the first time since the fall of the old kingdoms, Aethermere experienced prolonged stability. While hardships remained, large-scale conflict ceased. The King’s rule proved that unity—however strict—was preferable to annihilation.

⸻

Year 1290 — The Quiet Rebellions
Small pockets of dissent arose, often fueled by those who misunderstood the King’s purpose. These were resolved quickly and efficiently, preventing unnecessary suffering and maintaining peace for the wider population.

⸻

Year 1512 — The Renewal Projects
Efforts to restore the land intensified. Though progress was slow, regions once thought barren began to show signs of recovery. The King’s long vision continued to guide Aethermere toward a sustainable future.

⸻

Year 1786 — The Eternal Crown
By now, it was undeniable—the Sunless King did not age, nor falter. His immortality became a symbol of continuity in a broken world. Where rulers once rose and fell, bringing chaos with them, now there was only one constant.

⸻

Year 2000 — Present Day
Two millennia have passed since the Sunless King took the burden of the Scourge upon himself.

Aethermere endures.

Life is not easy—but it is stable. The horrors of the past have not returned. Magic is controlled. The Scourge is contained. The people survive under the watchful rule of a king who sacrificed everything to save them.

Some still whisper of freedom, of change, of a different world.

But history has shown what such desires bring.

And so, the Sunless King remains—
not as a tyrant, but as a necessity.
